<TITLE> Polls by October, demands Khaleda in first court appearance </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Sumon Mahmud bdnews24.com chief political correspondent Dhaka, June 1 (bdnews24.com)Detained former prime minister Khaleda Zia demanded that the state of emergency be lifted by the end of the month and elections be held by October, on Sunday, during her first court appearance since her arrest and detention last year. Criticising the present administration, Khaleda said that the caretaker government has been perpetuating its regime by sheer force. The BNP chairperson asked her party leaders and supporters to consolidate their unity at all costs, and called upon all other political parties to remain united. She claimed that all allegations brought against her were baseless and questioned the proceedings of the cases filed against her. Khaleda made the comments in court by permission of special judge Khondokar Kamaluzzaman who presided over the first hearing on charge framing against Khaleda in the Niko graft case. It was Khaleda's first public statement since her arrest and detention The former PM was earlier taken from special jail to the nearby Special Judge's Court-9, located on the Sangsad Bhaban complex, shortly after 11 am for the charge framing proceedings Two separate cases involving Canadian oil and gas company Niko Resources Ltd have been filed against former prime ministers Sheikh Hasina and Khaleda Zia, and were taken up by the court on May 26. Hasina was produced in special court on that day to face charges, but Khaleda was absent on the plea that she was indisposed. The BNP chairperson also faces charges in another corruption case that involves a controversial deal with GATCO. bdnews24.
